Contributing to CyberSecurity Demystified 🤝
First off, thank you for considering contributing to this project! It's people like you that make learning cybersecurity accessible and engaging for everyone.

1. The Welcome and Process
We welcome contributions that explain complex digital security concepts using simple, everyday analogies.

The Technical Workflow
Fork the repository to your own account.
Clone the project to your local machine.
Create a branch for your new analogy (git checkout -b feature/your-analogy-name).
Make your changes and add your new analogy.
Commit your changes (git commit -m 'Add [Concept] analogy').
Push to your fork (git push origin feature/your-analogy-name).
Open a Pull Request (PR) against the main repository.
2. Project-Specific Guidelines 🧠
To keep the field guide consistent and high-quality, please ensure your submissions meet the following criteria:

Use Physical-World Analogies: The core of this project is translating the digital into the physical (e.g., Firewalls as Castle Walls, Data Exfiltration as a Heist). Make sure your analogy is something a beginner interacts with in daily life.
Keep It Simple (Zero Jargon): If you must introduce a technical term (like "DDoS" or "Ransomware"), define it immediately within the context of your analogy.
Brevity is Key: Keep the analogy punchy. Aim for 2-4 bullet points max per concept, just like the existing entries in the project.
Format Consistently: Use the exact same Markdown formatting as seen in our README.md.
3. Wishlist
We are currently looking for analogies covering:

Ransomware
Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS)
Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) Attacks
Thank you for helping us demystify the digital battlefield! 🛡️
